<h3>Shared Property::<code>color</code></h3>

<h4>Overview</h4>
<div class="row">
    <p class="descriptive col-xs-12">
       Color can be set in one of two ways ... class-based and style-based. Starting with 'class-based' you'll see 
       again a catering to Bootstrap nominclature. If any of the following string are used for the <code>color</code>
       parameter then the coorsponding Bootstrap class will be used:
       <ul>
           <li>default</li>
           <li>success</li>
           <li>info</li>
           <li>primary</li>
           <li>warning</li>
           <li>error</li>
       </ul>

       If you're using bootstrap styling don't worry the style will be auto-magically set to the right name and 
       whatever monkeying around you've done with your bootstrap styling will be left in it's monkey state. This 
       is particularly monkey-good when you're using the LESS/SASS parameters of Bootstrap and you want them to carry
       through. Note, however, that there is no "huge" equivalent in Bootstrap. Ya can't have it all. 
   </p>
    <p class="descriptive col-xs-12">
       Now we must turn to a <em>sticky wicket</em> as they say in the industry.
       It turns out the property "size" is reserved by HTML5. Bastards. That's ok we're smarter than them ...
       well that's probably not true but still they're idea of <em>size</em> is really more a reflection of "length". For 
       that reason, we have taken the liberty of taking over the "size" property and if you want the HTML "size" you can 
       still get to that by setting "length". Fair?
    </p>        
    <p  class="descriptive col-xs-12">Happy days!</p>
</div>

<h4>Related Properties</h4>
<div class="row">
